events.html: • 1536 – Charles V makes a Royal Entry into Rome, demolishing a swath of the city to re-enact a Roman triumph.[4]

events.description: Two hundred Dutch noblemen, led by Hendrick van Brederode, force themselves into the presence of Margaret of Parma and present the Petition of Compromise, denouncing the Spanish Inquisition in the Seventeen Provinces.
events.html: • 1566 – Two hundred Dutch noblemen, led by Hendrick van Brederode, force themselves into the presence of Margaret of Parma and present the Petition of Compromise, denouncing the Spanish Inquisition in the Seventeen Provinces.[5]

events.description: In Virginia, Native American Pocahontas marries English colonist John Rolfe.

events.description: The Mayflower sets sail from Plymouth, Massachusetts on a return trip to England.
events.html: • 1621 – The Mayflower sets sail from Plymouth, Massachusetts on a return trip to England.[7]

events.html: • 1792 – United States President George Washington exercises his authority to veto a bill, the first time this power is used in the United States.[8]

entities.name: Veto power in the United States

events.description: Peace of Basel between France and Prussia is made.
events.html: • 1795 – Peace of Basel between France and Prussia is made.[9]

events.description: In the Battle of Maipú, Chile's independence movement, led by Bernardo O'Higgins and José de San Martín, win a decisive victory over Spain, leaving 2,000 Spaniards and 1,000 Chilean patriots dead.
events.html: • 1818 – In the Battle of Maipú, Chile's independence movement, led by Bernardo O'Higgins and José de San Martín, win a decisive victory over Spain, leaving 2,000 Spaniards and 1,000 Chilean patriots dead.[10]

events.description: American Civil War: The Battle of Yorktown begins.
events.html: • 1862 – American Civil War: The Battle of Yorktown begins.[11]

events.description: Bolivia declares war on Chile, and Chile declares war on Peru, starting the War of the Pacific.
events.html: • 1879 – Bolivia declares war on Chile, and Chile declares war on Peru, starting the War of the Pacific.[12]

events.description: A stand box collapses at Ibrox Park (now Ibrox Stadium) in Glasgow, Scotland, which led to the deaths of 25 and injuries to more than 500 supporters during an international association football match between Scotland and England.
events.html: • 1902 – A stand box collapses at Ibrox Park (now Ibrox Stadium) in Glasgow, Scotland, which led to the deaths of 25 and injuries to more than 500 supporters during an international association football match between Scotland and England.[13]

events.description: The Transandine Railway connecting Chile and Argentina is inaugurated.
events.html: • 1910 – The Transandine Railway connecting Chile and Argentina is inaugurated.[14]

events.description: The American Birth Control League, forerunner of Planned Parenthood, is incorporated.
events.html: • 1922 – The American Birth Control League, forerunner of Planned Parenthood, is incorporated.

events.description: Dominion of Newfoundland: Ten thousand rioters seize the Colonial Building leading to the end of self-government.
events.html: • 1932 – Dominion of Newfoundland: Ten thousand rioters seize the Colonial Building leading to the end of self-government.

events.description: U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt signs two executive orders: 6101 to establish the Civilian Conservation Corps, and 6102 "forbidding the Hoarding of Gold Coin, Gold Bullion, and Gold Certificates" by U.S. citizens.
events.html: • 1933 – U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt signs two executive orders: 6101 to establish the Civilian Conservation Corps, and 6102 "forbidding the Hoarding of Gold Coin, Gold Bullion, and Gold Certificates" by U.S. citizens.

events.description: Andorran Revolution: The Young Andorrans occupy the Casa de la Vall and force the government to hold democratic elections with universal male suffrage.
events.html: • 1933 – Andorran Revolution: The Young Andorrans occupy the Casa de la Vall and force the government to hold democratic elections with universal male suffrage.[15]

events.description: Tupelo–Gainesville tornado outbreak: An F5 tornado kills 233 in Tupelo, Mississippi.
events.html: • 1936 – Tupelo–Gainesville tornado outbreak: An F5 tornado kills 233 in Tupelo, Mississippi.

events.description: Spanish Civil War: Two days after the Nationalist army occupied the Catalan city of Lleida, dictator Francisco Franco decrees the abolition of the Generalitat (the autonomous government of Catalonia), the self-government granted by the Republic, and the official status of the Catalan language.
events.html: • 1938 – Spanish Civil War: Two days after the Nationalist army occupied the Catalan city of Lleida, dictator Francisco Franco decrees the abolition of the Generalitat (the autonomous government of Catalonia), the self-government granted by the Republic, and the official status of the Catalan language.[16]

events.description: World War II: Adolf Hitler issues Fuhrer Directive No. 41 summarizing Case Blue, including the German Sixth Army's planned assault on Stalingrad.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Adolf Hitler issues Fuhrer Directive No. 41 summarizing Case Blue, including the German Sixth Army's planned assault on Stalingrad.[17]

events.description: World War II: The Imperial Japanese Navy launches a carrier-based air attack on Colombo, Ceylon during the Indian Ocean raid. Port and civilian facilities are damaged and the Royal Navy cruisers HMS Cornwall and HMS Dorsetshire are sunk southwest of the island.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: The Imperial Japanese Navy launches a carrier-based air attack on Colombo, Ceylon during the Indian Ocean raid. Port and civilian facilities are damaged and the Royal Navy cruisers HMS Cornwall and HMS Dorsetshire are sunk southwest of the island.

events.description: World War II: United States Army Air Forces bomber aircraft accidentally cause more than 900 civilian deaths, including 209 children, and 1,300 wounded among the civilian population of the Belgian town of Mortsel. Their target was the Erla factory 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) from the residential area hit.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: United States Army Air Forces bomber aircraft accidentally cause more than 900 civilian deaths, including 209 children, and 1,300 wounded among the civilian population of the Belgian town of Mortsel. Their target was the Erla factory 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) from the residential area hit.

events.description: Cold War: Yugoslav leader Josip Broz Tito signs an agreement with the Soviet Union to allow "temporary entry of Soviet troops into Yugoslav territory".
events.html: • 1945 – Cold War: Yugoslav leader Josip Broz Tito signs an agreement with the Soviet Union to allow "temporary entry of Soviet troops into Yugoslav territory".

events.description: Soviet troops end their year-long occupation of the Danish island of Bornholm.
events.html: • 1946 – Soviet troops end their year-long occupation of the Danish island of Bornholm.

events.description: A Fleet Air Arm Vickers Wellington crashes into a residential area in Rabat, Malta during a training exercise, killing all 4 crew members and 16 civilians on the ground.
events.html: • 1946 – A Fleet Air Arm Vickers Wellington crashes into a residential area in Rabat, Malta during a training exercise, killing all 4 crew members and 16 civilians on the ground.[18][19]

events.description: A fire in a hospital in Effingham, Illinois, kills 77 people and leads to nationwide fire code improvements in the United States.
events.html: • 1949 – A fire in a hospital in Effingham, Illinois, kills 77 people and leads to nationwide fire code improvements in the United States.

events.description: Cold War: Ethel and Julius Rosenberg are sentenced to death for spying for the Soviet Union.
events.html: • 1951 – Cold War: Ethel and Julius Rosenberg are sentenced to death for spying for the Soviet Union.

events.description: Cuban Revolution: Fidel Castro declares himself at war with Cuban President Fulgencio Batista.
events.html: • 1956 – Cuban Revolution: Fidel Castro declares himself at war with Cuban President Fulgencio Batista.

events.description: Ripple Rock, an underwater threat to navigation in the Seymour Narrows in Canada is destroyed in one of the largest non-nuclear controlled explosions of the time.
events.html: • 1958 – Ripple Rock, an underwater threat to navigation in the Seymour Narrows in Canada is destroyed in one of the largest non-nuclear controlled explosions of the time.

events.description: During the Buddhist Uprising, South Vietnamese Prime Minister Nguyễn Cao Kỳ personally attempts to lead the capture of the restive city of Đà Nẵng before backing down.
events.html: • 1966 – During the Buddhist Uprising, South Vietnamese Prime Minister Nguyễn Cao Kỳ personally attempts to lead the capture of the restive city of Đà Nẵng before backing down.[20]

events.description: In Sri Lanka, Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna launches a revolt against the United Front government of Sirimavo Bandaranaike.
events.html: • 1971 – In Sri Lanka, Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna launches a revolt against the United Front government of Sirimavo Bandaranaike.

events.description: Carrie, the first novel by American author Stephen King, is published for the first time with a print run of 30,000 copies.
events.html: • 1974 – Carrie, the first novel by American author Stephen King, is published for the first time with a print run of 30,000 copies.[21][22]

events.description: In China, the April Fifth Movement leads to the Tiananmen Incident.
events.html: • 1976 – In China, the April Fifth Movement leads to the Tiananmen Incident.

events.description: The US Supreme Court rules that congressional legislation that diminished the size of the Sioux people's reservation thereby destroyed the tribe's jurisdictional authority over the area in Rosebud Sioux Tribe v. Kneip.
events.html: • 1977 – The US Supreme Court rules that congressional legislation that diminished the size of the Sioux people's reservation thereby destroyed the tribe's jurisdictional authority over the area in Rosebud Sioux Tribe v. Kneip.[23]

events.html: • 1991 – An ASA EMB 120 crashes in Brunswick, Georgia, killing all 23 aboard including Sen. John Tower and astronaut Sonny Carter.

events.description: The Space shuttle Atlantis launches on STS-37 to deploy the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory.
events.html: • 1991 – The Space shuttle Atlantis launches on STS-37 to deploy the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory.

events.html: • 1992 – Alberto Fujimori, president of Peru, dissolves the Peruvian congress by military force.

events.html: • 1992 – Peace protesters Suada Dilberovic and Olga Sučić are killed on the Vrbanja Bridge in Sarajevo, becoming the first casualties of the Bosnian War.

events.html: • 1998 – In Japan, the Akashi Kaikyō Bridge opens to traffic, becoming the longest bridge span in the world.
